I travel frequently with my family and take great care in researching creative food places for us to enjoy. While visiting New Orleans we went out of our way from our hotel to try this place and unfortunately it was a complete disappointment. For starters, do not go to this place expecting authentic Colombian food. We live in Florida, where Colombian restaurants can be found in abundance. The menu here is more along the lines of Colombian-fusion and well, the flavors were lacking. The empanadas were doughy and the filling was overly salted. The ceviche was average at best. The carne asada was cooked properly but lacked flavor, as did the accompanying sauce. The arepas, while presented beautifully, were just okay. I ordered a mule and had trouble tasting any rum in it at all. The service was poor and needs improvement. Upon entering we did not receive a warm welcome. After being seated, our waiter seemed to be more interested in providing attentive service to the others patrons around us while ignoring us for very long periods of time. After paying for our meal, we passed three employees behind the bar on our way to the door, and not a single one thanked us or bid us farewell. We came with the intention of having a great meal (our last dinner) before returning home, however, this place left much to be desired.

Recommended by friends who didn't get to go with us - their loss! We snagged a last minute reservation for a table at the 6 pm opening time, and joined a small crowd on the sidewalk a few minutes before the doors opened. Maïs is a smallish, attractive  space and was completely full within minutes.  Despite being slammed by the opening rush, servers were friendly and helpful. We ordered cocktails and two appetizer portions of empanadas and grilled corn. Cocktails were house specials, on point: a rosemary-scented riff on a pisco sour, and a rum/Cynar concoction. Both were very good, and the appetizers were even better, especially the corn.  For our main course we each ordered  an arepa, which is a thick sort of tortilla, split and filled with an amazing amount and variety of stuff, including relatively unfamiliar ingredients that typify Colombian cuisine, such as plantain and sweet potato. Arepas were delicious and *very* filling - we had no room left for dessert.  Maïs is a very popular spot, and a refreshing change from typical New Orleans cuisine. But seating is limited, so make reservations early.
